<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission from Cllr Jack Scott, Cabinet Member for Environment, Recycling and Streetscene, Sheffield City Council</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#a6a6a6; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">LGP 73</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Submission from Cllr Jack Scott, Cabinet Member for Environment, Recycling and Streetscene, Sheffield City Council</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local Government Procurement: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A Cabinet Member Perspective</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The scale and pace of changes in local government present </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significant challenges for Lead Members / Cabinet. In particular, the financial pressures faced by Local Authorities require more decisive and vis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ible leadership from Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. As Local Authorities seek to respond to unprecedented </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">challenge the importan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effective procurement, commissioning and contract management cannot be overestimated. It also poses unique challenges for Lead Members – coherent delivery of external work requires a fundamentally different set of skills and approach to managing in-h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ouse services. These are captured in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">summary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">note below. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Strategic Political </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Commissioning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In many large Metropolitan </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Districts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, up to 60% of expenditure is now outsourced. As a result, procurement and commissioning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have become vital components of delivering upon a political agenda and proactive place shaping.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lead Members need to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">equipped to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">able to articulate the outcome (rather than outputs) a specific procurement will achieve and set it within a broader poli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tical vision.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Early Engagement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Commissioning Cycle often starts over six months before a formal procurement is issued. Lead Members need to be involved well in advance if they are to effectively steer and shape the procurement in accordance with their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> political priorities and vision. There are tales of Lead Members simply being ‘consulted’ for signing off a procurement, rather than directing the process. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Market Intelligence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Prior to procurement, Lead Members need to understand the market for services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> they wish to procure themselves – it is insufficient to ask Officers to advise on this. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When undertaking procurement exercises, Lead Members </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">beset </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by provider interests – both external and internal to the Council. Lead Members need to be sufficient</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly agile to build effective personal relationships whilst avoiding accusations of bias or favoritism. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">User and Customer Involvement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As part of developing a coherent and articulate political vision, Lead Members need to be skilled in engaging and involvin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g users and customers and matching their expectations and requirements with political priorities and budget. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Financial Engineering and Performance Mechanisms</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many of the financial and performance products available in procurement are novel to Local Government, having been developed over the last decade or so. Particularly in the case of PFIs and working with banks, it is vital that Lead Members understand the l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evers and performance mechanisms within contracts if they are to sufficiently understand the gearing of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contracts to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hold providers to account. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Inspiring Innovation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lead Members should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">skilled </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to push providers for innovation and provide incentives for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">taking a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">balanced risk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approach. Without sufficient incentives and encouragement, outsourced projects can be stifled and hit their targets, whilst missing the point. This is particularly the case </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for long-term projects. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Visible Leadership and Accountability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ultimately, Lead Members </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recognize that they are responsible for the delivery or otherwise of contracted work. It is quite legitimate for Lead Members t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o share </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the successes when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contracts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">work well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, provided they also take responsibility when contractors fail to perform. Lead Members also need to understand the balance between setting employment practice standards and recognizing providers are the employers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The issues ra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ised above all merit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further consideration. They highlight a clear need for Lead Members to develop new skill sets and approaches </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in order </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">voter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">confidence, manage risk and generate innovation. Given the scale of the changes, L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocal Authorities should provide specific training to cover these issues for all Councillors, not just Lead Members. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>